docs.abstract: Federal officials want to lock in oversight to address police bias against African-Americans, an effort they fear will be abandoned by the new administration.
docs.snippet: Federal officials want to lock in oversight to address police bias against African-Americans, an effort they fear will be abandoned by the new administration.
docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — With just days until Donald J. Trump is sworn in as president, the Obama administration is making a last-minute push for police overhauls in two of the nation’s most violent cities, Baltimore and Chicago, where officers have been accused of routinely mistreating African-Americans.

headline.main: Obama Races to Overhaul Police in Baltimore and Chicago Before Trump Era
headline.print_headline: A Deadline  for a Drive  to Address  Police Bias

docs.abstract: At this year's event in Brooklyn and Manhattan, social justice is on the agenda.
docs.snippet: At this year's event in Brooklyn and Manhattan, social justice is on the agenda.
docs.lead_paragraph: The NYC Winter Jazzfest is best described as a hectic but euphoric convergence of musicians and fans in a range of spaces around Lower Manhattan and Brooklyn. Typically the sheer abundance of bands is the main story — an encouraging reminder of how much energy and curiosity reside in the current scene, whatever market indicators might say.

headline.main: Preview NYC Winter Jazzfest in 7 Tracks

docs.abstract: For years, Rudy Shepherd has made watercolor paintings to humanize people in the news.
docs.snippet: For years, Rudy Shepherd has made watercolor paintings to humanize people in the news.
docs.lead_paragraph: Five days after the massacre of nine black parishioners in Charleston, S.C., in 2015, the artist Rudy Shepherd painted 9-inch-by-12-inch portraits of two of the victims, Myra Thompson and Tywanza Sanders, and posted them to Instagram.

headline.main: Looking at an Artist’s Portraits of the Charleston Shooting Victims

docs.abstract: Kenya Barris, this ABC sitcom’s creator, and Anthony Anderson, its star, discuss an episode about the fallout from the presidential election.
docs.snippet: Kenya Barris, this ABC sitcom’s creator, and Anthony Anderson, its star, discuss an episode about the fallout from the presidential election.
docs.lead_paragraph: As Kenya Barris, the creator of ABC’s “black-ish,” and Anthony Anderson, that sitcom’s star, watched the 2016 presidential election results at their homes, they exchanged texts of increasing bafflement throughout the evening. “Then I woke up the next morning and said, I have to write about this,” Mr. Barris said. “I have something I want to say.”

headline.main: ‘black-ish’ Creator and Actor Again Walk on a Political Tightrope
headline.print_headline: A Sitcom Back on the High Wire

docs.abstract: In the digital present, captured here at the International Center of Photography, visual culture does more than reflect reality: For better and for worse, it creates it.
docs.snippet: In the digital present, captured here at the International Center of Photography, visual culture does more than reflect reality: For better and for worse, it creates it.
docs.lead_paragraph: In an interview, the singer Nina Simone once said, “An artist’s duty is to reflect the times,” by which she meant, basically, politics of the day, and in her case, racial politics. “I think that is true of painters, sculptors, poets, musicians,” she added. “As far as I’m concerned, it’s their choice, but I choose to reflect the times.”

headline.main: ‘Perpetual Revolution’ Shows Artists Shaping Their Times

docs.abstract: A new historical report prepared by the university illuminates how human bondage seeped into the life of the institution.
docs.snippet: A new historical report prepared by the university illuminates how human bondage seeped into the life of the institution.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 1755 a New York City newspaper carried an account of the swearing-in of the governors of the newly founded King’s College, which later grew into Columbia University. At the bottom of the page ran an advertisement for a rather different occasion: the sale of “TWO likely Negro Boys, and a Girl.”

headline.main: Columbia Unearths Its Ties to Slavery
headline.print_headline: Columbia Lays Out  Its Links to Slavery

docs.abstract: The centerpiece of a winter festival, two music-filled days downtown, had a sharp focus this year.
docs.snippet: The centerpiece of a winter festival, two music-filled days downtown, had a sharp focus this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: “The weight of rage/Can hold you back,” the poet Marvin Tate declared late on Friday, during the first night of the NYC Winter Jazzfest Marathon. “The weight of rage/Will hold you down,” he added, and then paused expectantly, as if holding onto a secret.

headline.main: Review: A Jazzfest Marathon With Protest at Its Heart
headline.print_headline: A Music Marathon With a Protest Vibe
